This is probably the most iconic recipe from puglia (italy) if you want to keep this dish as traditional as possible we recommend to do the orecchiette by yourself. If you can’t find cime di rapa you can use tender small broccoli rabe 🥦
.
3-4 pax .
Ingredients:
- 500gr (homemade) dried orecchiette
- 450 gr cime di rapa (broccoli rabe) washed, ends trimmed and cut into bite-sized pieces
- 5-6 tbsp olive oil
- 4-5 garlic cloves, sliced
- 2 shallots, sliced
- Optional red pepper flakes or chili sliced
.
Instructions:
.
Step 1
Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil.
.
Step 2
Add the cime di rapa or the broccoli rabe and the orecchiette to the water together and boil until the pasta is al dente.
.
Step 3
3 minutes before the pasta is ready heat the oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the garlic and the shallots until golden.
.
Step 3
Scoop out 1 cup of the pasta water and set aside. Scoop out the pasta and the brocoli with a large strainer and add with the cup of pasta water directly to the skillet. Stir carefully and serve with chili or red pepper. .
Buon appetito 💚
.

Dont we all add a little oil to our pot while boiling pasta. Well, we have been doing it wrong.
...
There is no hard evidence that putting oil in water prevents pasta from sticking. Since oil is not water soluble, it collects on top of the water and adheres to the pasta as water is poured out of the pot. Most professional chefs advise against putting oil in your pasta water because it creates slick, oily pasta that won’t adhere naturally to pasta sauce. Instead of using oil, stir pasta constantly to prevent sticking.

organic whole wheat pasta (penne) "bottarga & fennel & bordier seaweed butter"
・
・
パスタ好きの私。
美味しそうなパスタを見かけるとつい買ってしまう。
そんな話をしたら職場のシェフがこのパスタを教えてくれた。
…美味しい！！！！！
・
・
もうパスタそのものの香りが良いと言うのか何なのか、塩茹でしただけで既に美味しい。
鼻に抜けてゆく香りが好み過ぎて、危うくそのまま茹で立てを貪りそうになってしまった。
全粒粉パスタはいまいち好きになれない食感のが多い中、このパスタは食感もいい。
・
・
カレーのお供にするつもりだったんだけど、
シンプルに食べたくて予定変更。
はじめはボルディエバターの海藻タイプと、
ヒング少々で味付け。
・
・
途中、微量のフェンネルパウダーと
香りの良いExvオリーブオイルを垂らして和えたら、からすみパウダーをパラパラして味変。
美味しいに決まってるよね。
・
・

It was meant to be only a plate of pasta each for  @blueskiescottonclouds and I when we met for a spontaneously-arranged dinner. However, Chef @jason_vito82 persuaded us (to be frank, we hardly resisted 😂) to have an “omakase” instead. So we left it up to him to decide what to feed us. In no time at all, we were served some lovely sundried tomato tapenade and straciatella on toasted foccacia, followed closely by two fantastic seafood creations. First, large, sweet prawns from Vietnam in a luscious saffron aioli that we could not resist mopping up every bit of with the focaccia. Second, beautifully grilled, tender octopus with a pull-no-punches salsa verde, backed up by a chorus of chickpeas.
Then came a succession of pasta dishes, all showcasing their in-house-made fresh pasta, cooked to bullseye al dente-ness. Two were brand new lip-smacking creations with summer written all over them - a Farfelle (bow tie pasta) in a vibrant raspberry vinegar caponata (Sicilian-style sauce that’s chockfull of eggplant, celery and olives) rounded off by ricotta and jazzed up by crunchy pinenuts, and a Gnochetti Sardi. The latter, embellished in mascarpone and pistachio, had its chewy shell-shaped pasta simmered in red pesto made from sundried tomatoes and piquillo peppers. The final carb was an umami “celebr-ocean” of squid ink tagliolini crowned with uni, Hokkaido scallop and Indonesian baby squid. 
Dessert was a twist on the classic “Strawberries & Cream” with the fruit macerated in lemon juice, dusted in icing sugar and accompanied by smoked ricotta whipped cream, bitter hazelnut praline and fresh basil. It was heavenly.

Thanks Chefs @jason_vito82 @dannylaw93 @funeralformyself @yongern @thekneez for a great meal that really hit the spot!
